[cucumber/build] Pull request opened by davidjgoss

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/pull/33|#33 use latest node 12 lts>
<p>The Docker image is using Node 12.16.2, but the Node 12 LTS version is now 12.22.1, as used by <https://hub.docker.com/r/circleci/node/tags?page=1&amp;ordering=last_updated&amp;name=12|the CircleCI <code>node:12</code> image>.</p> <p>This should fix the build for <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/common/pull/1610">cucumber/common#1610</a>, where we added a new dependency that is hitting some kind of modules bug with the older Node version (but not the newer one).</p>

[cucumber/build] Comment on #34

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/pull/34#issuecomment-861552870|Comment on #34 :package: Release v0.5.2>
We have the branch constraint that the `release` branch should be linear (i.e. no merge commits) but merge commits are still allowed on `main`. So you _could_ merge `release` back to `main` afterwards, if you had to make any last-minute changes before release, but I think the protocol David suggested is better.

GitHub
2021-07-23 16:10:37

[cucumber/build] Comment on #39

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/pull/39#issuecomment-885956022|Comment on #39 Automate pre release (WIP)>
<p>OK I'm getting somewhere, but I have a design decision to make.</p> <p>Currently, we communicate the version number to be released by the <code>release.yaml</code> workflow by hard-coding it in that file, under the <code>env.version</code> key.</p> <p>We've been manually updating this to do a release, but if we want our pre-release workflow to do this, it's going to need additional permissions, because by default the <code>GITHUB_TOKEN</code> can't update workflows.</p> <p>The easy option would be to use a token with the <code>workflows</code> permission, but that seems like a bad idea for security reasons.</p> <p>As an alternative, that <code>release.yaml</code> workflow needs to read the version-to-be-released from somewhere else. I guess we can use a file.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build">cucumber/build</a>
incoming-webhook (https://cucumberbdd.slack.com/services/B022R1P38SX)
2021-07-23 16:15:02

GitHub
2021-07-25 01:03:58

[cucumber/build] Issue opened by mattwynne

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42|#42 Automate releases>
<p>This effort is almost there. We have a PR being created (e.g. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build/pull/43">#43</a>) when you update the <code>CHANGELOG.md</code> file, adding a new numbered version header.</p> <p>There are a couple of snags, however, to do with the current solution of using a <code>VERSION</code> file to represent the version to be released / last released.</p> <p>• In <code>pre-release.yaml</code>, read the current release version from the git tags instead. This will mean we don't need to make a new commit in the release PR, and so we don't need to worry about GPG signing that commit. In fact we can rebase rather than squash since the <code>main</code> branch has a rule to enforce linear history as well as signed commits. That will make the release PR nicer to review. • in <code>release.yaml</code>, just read the version to be released from <code>changelog latest</code>.</p>
Comments
2
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build">cucumber/build</a>
GitHub
2021-07-25 01:20:03

[cucumber/build] Comment on #42

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42#issuecomment-886165524|Comment on #42 Automate releases>
<p>Okay, the work on removing the <code>VERSION</code> file is done, and appears to have worked.</p> <p>The rebasing idea has not, however. Old commits that have been squashed into the release branch are being rebased on, from before we had the commit signing rule on main.</p> <p>Perhaps we need to re-branch the <code>release</code> branch from main as of the last release.</p>

[cucumber/build] Comment on #42

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42#issuecomment-888122381|Comment on #42 Automate releases>
<p>I would like to enforce the security of automated releases.</p> <p>To do so, I would like to set action permissions, in the "Actions" settings, to "local actions only", or maybe "Allow select actions" with only the ones from github.</p> <p><a href="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24386780/127290430-d68b78cc-7db3-4b79-baa3-e87aaaf8ed76.png">image</a></p> <p>External actions are a <a href="https://www.upguard.com/blog/supply-chain-attack">supply chain attack</a> vector. That would result in a breach into the cucumber build mechanism which is used to release all cucumber things.</p> <p>Preventing this would mean, in <code>pre-release.yml</code>, avoid reading the changelog with an external action, and avoid creating the realease PR with another one.</p> <p><code>mattwynne/changelog-action</code> is a fork, based on the docker image <code>mattwynne/changelog</code> which is also a fork with a binary in it written in go. A lot can go wrong here.</p> <p>And <code>peter-evans/create-pull-request</code> is totally out of sight.</p> <p>In <code>release.yml</code>, there are also a lot of dependencies out of our sight. At the moment as the release still require some human review, that is barely an issue. But as it is planned to automate all the things, I think we should be more careful with those dependencies.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build">cucumber/build</a>
GitHub
2021-07-28 08:14:45

[cucumber/build] Issue opened by mattwynne

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/45|#45 Use layer caching to speed up Build / Release workflows>
<p>The <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build/actions/workflows/build.yaml"><code>Build</code></a> workflow, which is a required status check, takes about an hour to run.</p> <p>When we run the <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build/actions/workflows/release.yaml"><code>Release</code></a> workflow we have to rebuild the container again from scratch, because we don't have any of the layers cached.</p> <p><a href="https://evilmartians.com/chronicles/build-images-on-github-actions-with-docker-layer-caching#the-cache-dance-off">This blog post</a> could be a good starting point for how to use GitHub's cache.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build">cucumber/build</a>
GitHub
2021-07-28 09:49:00

[cucumber/build] Comment on #42

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42#issuecomment-888462482|Comment on #42 Automate releases>
<p>Aurélin and I paired today. We did some mitigation of the chances of a supply chain attack on the GitHub Actions plugins by choosing the "Allow select actions" and adding the two 3rd party ones we're using to the list.</p> <p>Ultimately, we think it might be best to fork those 3rd party plugins to the Cucumber org, and choose the "Use local actions only" option.</p>

[cucumber/build] Comment on #42

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42#issuecomment-888565950|Comment on #42 Automate releases>
<p>We have an issue that, if the pre-release script runs <em>while a release is still in progress</em> (i.e. you push a new commit to <code>main</code> before the new release's <code>vx.y.z</code> tag has been pushed) then it will still trigger, thinking that the release has not happened yet:</p> <p>e.g. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build/runs/3185235101">https://github.com/cucumber/build/runs/3185235101</a></p> <p>I guess we need a way to signal to the script that the release is in progress, too. Maybe we can add the git tag at the beginning of the <code>release.yaml</code> instead of at the end?</p>

[cucumber/build] Comment on #42

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42#issuecomment-889139240|Comment on #42 Automate releases>
<p>I may have found a working and simpler workflow based on a single <code>release</code> branch and using only merge. No rebase, no squash.</p> <p>TL;DR:</p> <p>• checkout a brand new <code>release</code> branch from <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build/commit/7854135920aa38b55acc4934c8c67db001883dac">7854135</a> • when pre-releasing, checkout a new <code>pre-release</code> branch from main • create a PR for the <code>pre-release</code> based on the <code>release</code> branch • to release, merge the <code>pre-release</code> branch on <code>release</code>, and tag the current commit</p> <p>Long version:</p> <p>We would have to recreate a release branch from the following commit, because this is the last one on master before 0.6.0: <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build/commit/7854135920aa38b55acc4934c8c67db001883dac">7854135</a></p> <p>(the tag v0.6.0 is not usable: it point to a commit that does not exists on main).</p> <p>So that would looks like this:</p> <pre><code>$ git show-branch ! [main] Update README.md ** [release] Tweak working in release PR -- + [main] Update README.md + [main^] Update docs for automated release workflow (#47) + [main~2] Introduce Docker layer cache (#46) + [main~3] Report version numbers detected + [main~4] Fix + [main~5] Fix copy/paste error + [main~6] Parse version number correctly from changelog + [main~7] YAML + [main~8] Not sure why this needs an author + [main~9] Always take changes from `main` if there's a conflict + [main~10] One-branch-per-release was not finished in the previous commit + [main~11] Use one branch per release + [main~12] Trigger build + [main~13] Fix CHANGELOG titles + [main~14] Use more consistent name + [main~15] Update CHANGELOG for #35 + [main~16] Merge #35 + [main~17] Add CHANGELOG entry for &lt;https://github.com/cucumber/build/pull/38&gt; + [main~18] Update Perl dependencies (#38) + [main~19] Fix links in CHANGELOG + [main~20] Fix diff link in 6.0.0 header +** [release] Tweak working in release PR </code></pre> <p>To pre-release, simply checkout a new <code>pre-release</code> branch from <code>main</code></p> <pre><code>$ git checkout main Switched to branch 'main' Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'. $ git checkout -b pre-release Switched to a new branch 'pre-release' $ git show-branch ! [main] Update README.md ** [pre-release] Update README.md ! [release] Tweak working in release PR --- +** [main] Update README.md +** [main^] Update docs for automated release workflow (#47) +** [main~2] Introduce Docker layer cache (#46) +** [main~3] Report version numbers detected +** [main~4] Fix +** [main~5] Fix copy/paste error +** [main~6] Parse version number correctly from changelog +** [main~7] YAML +** [main~8] Not sure why this needs an author +** [main~9] Always take changes from `main` if there's a conflict +** [main~10] One-branch-per-release was not finished in the previous commit +** [main~11] Use one branch per release +** [main~12] Trigger build +** [main~13] Fix CHANGELOG titles +** [main~14] Use more consistent name +** [main~15] Update CHANGELOG for #35 +** [main~16] Merge #35 +** [main~17] Add CHANGELOG entry for &lt;https://github.com/cucumber/build/pull/38&gt; +** [main~18] Update Perl dependencies (#38) +** [main~19] Fix links in CHANGELOG +** [main~20] Fix diff link in 6.0.0 header +**+ [release] Tweak working in release PR </code></pre> <p><code>main</code> and <code>pre-release</code> have the same HEAD<br /> <code>release</code> still has the HEAD from the previous release</p> <p>Now, if we create a PR to merge <code>pre-release</code> on <code>release</code>, we will be able to review the diff between the previous release and the new proposed one:</p> <pre><code>$ git log --oneline release..pre-release b2f594b (origin/main, origin/HEAD, pre-release, main) Update README.md e9fc872 Update docs for automated release workflow (#47) fec71a8 Introduce Docker layer cache (#46) 2a821bd Report version numbers detected 486f167 Fix 89cea8a Fix copy/paste error f91c4a8 Parse version number correctly from changelog a2b919f YAML d61fd21 Not sure why this needs an author e96d523 Always take changes from `main` if there's a conflict 99af31b One-branch-per-release was not finished in the previous commit 8701c1c Use one branch per release 2233ee6 Trigger build 177550d Fix CHANGELOG titles ff8aaee Use more consistent name bdc3157 Update CHANGELOG for #35 0e8c7e7 Merge #35 c61991f Add CHANGELOG entry for &lt;https://github.com/cucumber/build/pull/38&gt; bf25f4d Update Perl dependencies (#38) f4cefd3 Fix links in CHANGELOG 898cb77 Fix diff link in 6.0.0 header </code></pre> <p>To finalize the release, just merge pre-release into release. No rebase (so no squash), just merge.</p> <pre><code>$ git merge pre-release Updating 7854135..b2f594b Fast-forward .github/workflows/build.yaml | 22 +++++++++++++++++++++- .github/workflows/pre-release.yaml | 25 +++++++++++++++++++------ .github/workflows/release.yaml | 2 +- CHANGELOG.md | 35 +++++++++++++++++++---------------- Dockerfile | 9 ++++----- Makefile | 6 +++++- README.md | 41 +++++++---------------------------------- scripts/{download-chrome.sh =&amp;gt; install-chromium.sh} | 2 +- 8 files changed, 77 insertions(+), 65 deletions(-) rename scripts/{download-chrome.sh =&amp;gt; install-chromium.sh} (95%) $ git show-branch ! [main] Update README.md ! [pre-release] Update README.md ** [release] Update README.md --- ++** [main] Update README.md </code></pre> <p><code>release</code> now points to the last commit we wanted to actually release. <code>main</code> and <code>release</code> have the same history, and we can add a tag to that released commit. The HEAD of release is the same commit as the one that has been released from main, not another one. That way we can reproduce the process for the next time.</p> <pre><code>$ git checkout main Already on 'main' Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'. $ git show --compact-summary commit b2f594bc26d15604460b791de11356a1f3429bbe (HEAD -&amp;gt; main, origin/main, origin/HEAD, release, pre-release) # ... </code></pre>

[cucumber/build] Comment on #49

[cucumber/build] Comment on #42

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42#issuecomment-889488349|Comment on #42 Automate releases>
<p>I think we should abandon the 3rd party pull request action and use <code>gh</code>. It's natively supported in GitHub Actions anyway. I've done a proof of concept here: <a href="https://github.com/mattwynne/release-workflow-test">https://github.com/mattwynne/release-workflow-test</a></p> <p>I think it will work much better, but we still have the nagging problem of the potential that someone could use a squash merge commit to the release branch and fuck it all up.</p> <p>Maybe we should try a different approach, and look into using <em>deployments</em> instead. <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/actions/managing-workflow-runs/reviewing-deployments">https://docs.github.com/en/actions/managing-workflow-runs/reviewing-deployments</a></p>

[cucumber/build] Comment on #42

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42#issuecomment-892202830|Comment on #42 Automate releases>
<p>I really like the PR-based approval step in the workflow. The pull request allows us to clearly see exactly what's going into the release.</p> <p>However, this model creates some tension:</p> <ol><li>We'd like to enforce linear, signed commits on <code>main</code>, by allowing feature branches to be squashed by the core team member who merges the change, instead of having them make a merge commit.</li><li>GitHub's rules about merge strategies are per-repo, not per-branch, so this also means release PRs would end up as squashed commits to the <code>release</code> branch too. There's no way I can see to prevent this, other than by convention.</li><li>If we end up with a squashed commit to the <code>release</code> branch, we break the git history on that branch. This makes subsequent releases hard, as git will try to merge the commits from previous releases into that branch again, potentially creating merge conflicts, but also making the release PR hard to read as it contains more commits than are really being released. Also, if a tag is put on the released commit, it's not showing on <code>main</code> where the original commit was.</li> </ol> <p>Ideally, I think, we'd have squash merges to <code>main</code> and merge commits to <code>release</code>, but GitHub won't let us enforce this.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build">cucumber/build</a>
GitHub
2021-08-03 16:51:12

[cucumber/build] Comment on #42

<https://github.com/cucumber/build/issues/42#issuecomment-892396505|Comment on #42 Automate releases>
<p>OK I have something that seems to work in <a href="https://github.com/mattwynne/release-workflow">https://github.com/mattwynne/release-workflow</a></p> <p>It works by creating two branches in the <code>pre-release</code> workflow:</p> <p>• a <code>pre-release/vx.y.z</code> branch off <code>main</code> when you trigger the release • a <code>release/vx.y.z</code> branch off the <em>previous</em> release version</p> <p>Then it makes a PR onto that <code>release/vx.y.z</code> branch from the <code>pre-release/vx.y.z</code> branch that contains the new commits.</p> <p>Once the PR is merged into the <code>release/**</code> branch, the <code>release</code> workflow runs, creates a GitHub Release, and even if there's a squash merge commit, that still seems to tag the commit on <code>main</code>, rather than the throwaway squash commit.</p> <p>I think the next step might be to factor out some re-usable (and perhaps even testable!) actions from that spike, so that we can use them here.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build">cucumber/build</a>
GitHub

<p>I've updated the <code>pre-release</code> and <code>release</code> actions workflows in this repo, and the <code>pre-release</code> one <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build/pull/52">seems to have worked</a>.</p> <p>I had some trouble bootstrapping it:</p> <ol><li>I had to move the tag 😲 for v0.6.0 as it was pointing to one of those ugly squashed commits, so I moved it back to the <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/build/commit/b34ac5abc308f4e3247f5a040e80ff5a3afa8f8c">relevant commit</a> on <code>main</code>.</li><li>creating the <code>release/0.7.0</code> branch failed with <code>refusing to allow a GitHub App to create or update workflow ".github/workflows/pre-release.yaml" without "workflows" permission</code> which I <em>think</em> is because the diff for this release includes changes to the workflow file, which the bot is not allowed to make. I worked around it by manually pushing the <code>release/0.7.0</code> branch from the (corrected) <code>v0.6.0</code> tag.</li> </ol>
